  <discussion>Pisonia capitata is represented in the flora by a single, possibly clonal,
        population of a few pistillate plants in south-central Arizona several hundred kilometers
        north of known populations in Sonora, perhaps originating from a freak event of bird
        dispersal. Plants are not known to have set seed.</discussion>
  <discussion>As noted above, pistillate plants of Pisonia capitata and P. aculeata exhibit no
        apparent differences, nor are there apparent vegetative differences between the species.
        That plants known in the flora truly represent P. aculeata is an assumption based on
        geography.</discussion>
